>> The document was simply called an F. A. Q. and it was a very detailed des=
cription of our mission, our stakeholders and our values, and just as import=
antly, what we didn't value and who wasn't a stakeholder. it described the t=
hings our business was predicated on and included the criterion by which we c=
ould know when it was time to shut down. It informed everything we did. It w=
as a statement of philosophy as much as anything else.
>>=20
>> About 9 years in another firm expressed an interest in buying a majority s=
take in my business. They asked me to bring a business plan, create a pitch b=
ook and give a half hour presentation to their chief investment officer.
>>=20
>> I did none of that.
>>=20
>> Instead I bought our F. A. Q. and began going through it.
>>=20
>> The CIO turned beet red. He said, "What's this shit? I want to see pro-fo=
rmas, I want to see technology, I want to see plans. I need R. O. I."
>>=20
>> I said, "If we don't agree on first principles then the only thing you wi=
ll ever be is a competitor, and there is no way I'm sharing any of that with=
 you. Your time is valuable, but so is mine. You said you'd give me 30 minut=
es and I'm taking it. Now, shut up and pay attention."
>>=20
>> I walked him through the document. About 15 minutes in his demeanor softe=
ned and as I approached the end he began laughing.
>>=20
>> He said, "I've been doing this for 22 years and in no instance did a busi=
ness plan survive the first year. And, in every instance where a business fe=
ll apart it was because they and we didn't see eye-to-eye on one of the thin=
gs you've addressed. I like what you've done and I want to invest in your bu=
siness."
>>=20
>> I said, "What business? I haven't even told you what we do yet."
>>=20
>> He said, "I don't care. Any business you can run on these terms I want to=
 be a part of."
>>=20
>> I told him that the biggest risk to our business was not to the market or=
 to our ideas but to the character of our investors. For that reason, the ne=
xt step was that I needed to interview him, his staff and his major investor=
s so that I might judge their character and determine what principles they l=
ive by.
>>=20
>> He agreed to that and I spent a half day with them. I even composed a wri=
tten test and collected impromptu essays from them. Even if they had not her=
etofore lived according to the words they gave me I made it clear I would ho=
ld them to their rhetoric henceforth.
>>=20
>> They did pretty well, so I gave them a final test. I had a competing offe=
r from another firm that was not structured as an equity stake but an invest=
ment management and IP deal where I retained 100% ownership.=20
>>=20
>> Because if the investor bought into my company then we'd be partners work=
ing for the benefit of both of us, I told them to evaluate both the competin=
g deal and their own and give me a recommendation and I'd do what they sugge=
st. But, they had to understand that if they recommended I go with them and l=
ater I found out they did it because it was in their best interest but not m=
ine then they would have one hell of a pissed-off partner.
>>=20
>> They did as I asked and spent a day with the competition getting the deta=
ils of their deal and auditing their character.
>>=20
>> Then they gave me a report recommending I go with the competition and not=
 them.
>>=20
>> This is the power of well-articulated and well-lived mission and values. O=
ften when  an investor comes along people start seeing an exit strategy and d=
ollar signs and start jumping through absurd hoops that can often destroy th=
eir focus and even their business.
>>=20
>> I didn't have to do that. I had a long-standing document that guided our b=
ehavior and that gave me the courage to dictate terms and interact with othe=
rs as I did.=20
>>=20
>> After auditing the investor's character I didn't have to do anything. The=
y are the ones, for example, who created a business plan for a business as t=
hey could imagine it after we were partners and they submitted it to me for m=
y approval. And they are the ones who compared that to the competition and t=
hey determined their offer was inferior.
>>=20
>> We really didn't have to do anything except be who we are and hold them t=
o who they said they were.=20
>>=20
>> That is what character is; it is who we are. The first step is to say who=
 that is so you can know who to be when things get confusing. There were ple=
nty of well-run endeavors before the mobile device, the personal computer an=
d even before the discovery of electricity.
>>=20
>> There is power in the written word, and IMHO the word and the will are bo=
th necessary and sufficient. That document was everything and I don't think o=
ur performance could have been improved by an app.=20
>>=20
>> If you'd like to discuss values and culture then I'd like to send you tha=
t document if you think you'll have time to read it by next week.
>>=20
>> Brooke
